<h4>MORE HEALTH NEWS</h4>

<ul><li><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/18/eating-disorders-anorexia/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>Colorado eating disorder patients say they&#8217;ve been subjected to nude weigh-ins, forced to eat nonvegan foods.</strong></a><strong> </strong>As we&#8217;ve reported before, Colorado is a national hub for eating disorder treatment. But the state does not regulate centers&#8217; treatment plans or clinical practices â€” it only conducts inspections for safety issues and after complaints. That could change under a bill being debated at the state Capitol. The aim, reports <strong>Jennifer Brown</strong>, is to crack down on what patients say are abusive practices.<strong><br></strong><strong>â€” The Colorado Sun</strong></li>

<li><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/18/colorado-medicaid-psychiatric-facility-reimbursement/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>Coloradans with Medicaid and serious mental illness could soon receive better care at certain facilities.</strong></a><strong> </strong>A decades-old federal Medicaid policy often results in patients who are receiving health care for serious mental illnesses being kicked out of treatment facilities too soon. But Colorado lawmakers are working to change that, <strong>Tatiana Flowers</strong> reports. A bill in the legislature would send an additional $7.2 million to the state&#8217;s Medicaid agency to help care for patients who need a longer stay.<strong><br></strong><strong>â€” The Colorado Sun</strong></li>

<li><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/19/excited-delirium-colorado-law-elijah-mcclain/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>As states, including Colorado, target disavowed &#8220;excited delirium&#8221; diagnosis, police groups push back.</strong></a><strong> </strong>The diagnosis &#8220;excited delirium&#8221; has a long history of use in cases where someone dies during an encounter with police. Support among medical professionals for the diagnosis is crumbling, though, and states, including Colorado, are working to ban the term. But, as <strong>Renuka Rayasam</strong> reports, law enforcement organizations are fighting the bans, including one group that has invoked the First Amendment.<strong><br></strong><strong>â€” KFF Health News</strong></li>

<li><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/20/a-western-slope-program-is-helping-older-coloradans-maintain-independence/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>A Western Slope program is helping older Coloradans maintain independence.</strong></a><strong> </strong>The federal <strong>Centers for Medicare &amp; Medicaid Services</strong> runs a program called <strong>PACE</strong>, for <strong>Program of All-Inclusive Care for the Elderly</strong>. That&#8217;s a chunky bit of acronym soup, but here&#8217;s what it means for older Coloradans in Grand Junction: help at home, quality meals and transportation to places where they can meet up with friends and receive support services and care for basic hygiene needs. As <strong>Nancy Lofholm</strong> reports, this model could greatly benefit other communities, too, but not every place has the resources to manage the notoriously complicated program.<strong><br></strong><strong>â€” The Colorado Trust</strong></li>
</ul>

