<h4>MORE CLIMATE NEWS</h4>

<ul><li><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/14/ethylene-oxide-lakewood-terumo-epa-colorado/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>EPA puts new limits on toxic ethylene oxide, Terumo.</strong></a><strong> </strong>Clean air advocates and health scientists have long demanded far tougher limits on plants that emit ethylene oxide into neighborhoods after using the toxic gas to sterilize medical equipment. Terumo, which says it complies with all limits, in Lakewood is a target of lawsuits. Now the EPA is cracking down nationally on EtO emissions. <strong><br></strong><strong>â€” The Colorado Sun</strong></li>

<li><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/14/colorado-rental-car-fee-increase-passenger-rail/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>New fee could fund part of a Colorado passenger train expansion.</strong></a><strong> </strong>While the overall plan for expanded passenger rail is still sketchy, lawmakers appear ready to start raising money for it. Some legislators are backing a rental car fee to help draw more federal money for more rail, <strong>Jesse Paul</strong> reports.<strong><br></strong><strong>â€” The Colorado Sun</strong></li>

<li><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/13/colorado-recycling-expansion-costs-critics/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>Colorado recycling expansion just got a lot pricier.</strong></a><strong> </strong>While the Colorado companies that rely heavily on consumer packaging plan for a new fee to fund expanded recycling statewide, the price for the potential services keeps going up, <strong>Michael Booth</strong> reports. Lawmakers have to choose one of the price scenarios before planning can continue.<strong><br></strong><strong>â€” The Colorado Sun</strong></li>

<li><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/19/weekend-storms-colorado-mountain-snowpack-above-average-levels/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>Snowstorm the size of a large state buries dust storm the size of a large state.</strong></a> The mega-snow from last week buried Colorado river basins in a healthy snowpack, <strong>Shannon Mullane</strong> reports. But because we can&#8217;t have nice things, scientists also note there was previously a big dust storm that will eventually speed up snowmelt when it&#8217;s uncovered in the spring.<strong><br></strong><strong>â€” The Colorado Sun</strong></li>
</ul>

